Now,
\begin{align*}
(1 + x)^{1000} & = \sum_{i = 0}^{1000}\binom{1000}{i}x^i
\end{align*}
and
\begin{align*}
(1 + x)^{999} & = \sum_{i = 0}^{999}\binom{999}{i}x^i.
\end{align*}
From the second equation, let's multiply the RHS of both sides by $2x$ and switch the power of $x$ from the lower one to the upper one. Then, the equation transforms to
\begin{align*}
2x(1 + x)^{999} & = \sum_{i = 0}^{999}\left(2\binom{999}{i} \cdot x^{i+1}\right)
\end{align*}
Similarly, by applying the same idea to
\begin{align*}
(1 + x)^{n-1} & = \sum_{i = 0}^{n-1}\binom{n - 1}{k}x^i,
\end{align*}
we can transform it to
\begin{align*}
(1 + x)^{n} & = \sum_{i = 0}^{n}\binom{n}{i}x^i,
\end{align*}
and the coefficient of $x^{50}$ of this equation can be expressed in the form
\begin{align*}
\binom{i}{50} + 1001\binom{i + 1}{50} + \dotsb + \binom{n}{50}.
\end{align*}</think>

